e":"1190–Zesnulá","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1260":"1260","England":"Anglie","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1190–":"1190–Afdød","1190–Male":"1190–Afdød","1235–1260":"1235–1260","1190–Female":"1190–Afdød","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1260":"1260","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"1190–":"1190–Overleden","1190–Male":"1190–Overleden","1235–1260":"1235–1260","1190–Female":"1190–Overleden","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1260":"1260","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1190–":"1190–Deceased","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1235–1260":"1235–1260","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1260":"1260","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coventry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of Coventry in the West Midlands, which is probably named with the genitive case of an Old English personal name <i>Cofa</i> (compare   Coveney  ) + Old English <i>trēow</i> ‘tree’. This name is now common in eastern Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Coveney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamonn.","English (Kent): habitational name from a place in Cambridgeshire named Coveney, from either the genitive case of Old English <i>cofa</i> ‘shelter’ (see   Cove  ) or of a personal name <i>Cofa</i> (of uncertain origin) + Old English <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. This surname is also established in Ireland, where it is more probably a phonetic Anglicization of an Irish name. See sense 2.","Irish (Cork): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Coibhdheanaigh</b> or <b>Mac Coibhdheanaigh</b> ‘descendant’ or ‘son’ of <i>Coibhdheanach</i>, a personal name derived from the Irish word <i>coibhdhean</i> ‘(marauding) troop, raiding party’."]}]},{"name":"Amy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."],"variants":[{"name":"Aimie","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]},{"name":"Aimée","meanings":["originally a vernacular nickname meaning ‘beloved’, from the past participle of French <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’ (Latin <i>amare</i>;  compare  Amy  ). It has been in use in French since the Middle Ages, although it has never been very common. It is now also used, with or without the accent, as a given name in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Amie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Amy  , corresponding in form to the French vocabulary word meaning ‘(female) friend’."]},{"name":"Ami","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":69,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Amy Coventry was born in 1190, in England. She had at least 1 son with Alonzo Farnell."},"et":{"1190–":"1190–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1235–1260":"1235–1260","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1260":"1260","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1190–":"1190–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1235–1260":"1235–1260","1190–Female":